===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A large [[building]] that is [[fortified]] and contains many [[defence]]s; in previous ages often inhabited by a [[nobleman]] or [[king]].
# {{lb|en|chess}} An instance of [[castling]].
# {{lb|en|shogi}} A defense structure in Japanese chess in which the king (玉) is positioned in a certain way so that it is protected by pawns (歩) and silver general(s) (銀) and/or gold general(s) (金) often with an additional knight (桂) and lance (香車).
# {{lb|en|chess|informal}} A [[rook]]; a [[chess]] piece shaped like a castle [[tower]].
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[close helmet]].
#* {{quote-text|year=1786|author=Francis Grose|title=A Treatise on Ancient Armour and Weapons|page=12|passage=The '''castle''' was perhaps a figurative name for a close headpiece deduced from its enclosing and defending the head, as a castle did the whole body; or a corruption from the Old French word ''[[casquetel]]'', a small or light helmet.}}
# {{lb|en|dated}} Any strong, imposing, and stately mansion.
# {{lb|en|dated}} A small tower, as on a ship, or an elephant's back.

====Usage notes====
For the chess piece, chess players prefer the term [[rook]].

